"`collision/define-layers!` sorts entities into named bins so the
engine can skip collision checks between bins that don't need to
collide. This cuts collision cost from O(n^2) to something much
smaller AND lets you express game rules cleanly. This appendix is
the recipe file.

## The pattern

```scheme
(collision/define-layers!
 '((layer-name :collides-with (other-layer-name ...))
   ...))
(entity/layer! ent 'layer-name)
```

Every layer lists what it CAN hit. The engine looks up the pair at
collision time and skips if not in the list. Reciprocal? Not
required — 'a collides with b' can be true while 'b collides with a'
is false. But typical usage keeps them symmetric.

## Recipe 1 — Basic shmup

Player, enemy, player-bullet, enemy-bullet.

```scheme
(collision/define-layers!
 '((player       :collides-with (enemy enemy-bullet))
   (enemy        :collides-with (player player-bullet))
   (player-bullet :collides-with (enemy))
   (enemy-bullet  :collides-with (player))))
```

Rules encoded: player takes damage from enemy or enemy-bullet.
Player-bullet kills enemy. No friendly fire. No player-bullet vs
enemy-bullet (bullets pass through each other).

## Recipe 2 — Bullet-vs-bullet cancels

Same as basic, plus bullets can deflect.

```scheme
(collision/define-layers!
 '((player       :collides-with (enemy enemy-bullet))
   (enemy        :collides-with (player player-bullet))
   (player-bullet :collides-with (enemy enemy-bullet))
   (enemy-bullet  :collides-with (player player-bullet))))
```

Now bullets can destroy each other. Kids can 'shoot down' incoming
bullets. Adds a defensive layer to the shmup.

## Recipe 3 — Platformer with pickups

```scheme
(collision/define-layers!
 '((player :collides-with (ground enemy pickup))
   (ground :collides-with (player enemy))
   (enemy  :collides-with (player ground))
   (pickup :collides-with (player))))
```

Enemies walk on ground (won't fall through). Pickups don't interact
with anything except player.

## Recipe 4 — Multi-team fight

Team A vs Team B. Bullets from each team hit the other.

```scheme
(collision/define-layers!
 '((team-a          :collides-with (team-b team-b-bullet))
   (team-b          :collides-with (team-a team-a-bullet))
   (team-a-bullet   :collides-with (team-b))
   (team-b-bullet   :collides-with (team-a))))
```

## Recipe 5 — Racing (no collision between racers)

Racers pass through each other; only interact with the track and
obstacles.

```scheme
(collision/define-layers!
 '((racer    :collides-with (obstacle finish-line))
   (obstacle :collides-with (racer))
   (finish-line :collides-with (racer))))
```

## Recipe 6 — Ghost mode (temporary phase-through)

Player has an invincibility state where they pass through enemies.
Solution: two player layers.

```scheme
(collision/define-layers!
 '((player       :collides-with (enemy enemy-bullet))
   (player-ghost :collides-with ())
   (enemy        :collides-with (player player-bullet))
   (enemy-bullet :collides-with (player))
   (player-bullet :collides-with (enemy))))

;; Switch layer during ghost mode:
(entity/layer! player 'player-ghost)
;; Later, restore:
(entity/layer! player 'player)
```

## Recipe 7 — Environmental layers

Water tiles interact with sinking things; air tiles with flying.

```scheme
(collision/define-layers!
 '((swimmer :collides-with (water shore))
   (flyer   :collides-with (bird shore))
   (walker  :collides-with (shore ground))
   (water   :collides-with (swimmer))
   (bird    :collides-with (flyer))
   (shore   :collides-with (swimmer flyer walker))
   (ground  :collides-with (walker))))
```

Same physics engine; different rules for different creature types.

## Recipe 8 — Debug all-vs-all

Development-time only.

```scheme
(collision/define-layers!
 '((all :collides-with (all))))
```

Then set every entity to layer 'all. See EVERY collision. Useful
when debugging why something isn't hitting.

## Cost model

Roughly: for each entity in a layer, the engine checks against
entities in layers it can hit. With N entities across L layers with
average pair-count K, cost is O(N * K). Well-partitioned layers keep
K small; unpartitioned worlds have K ~ N and cost N^2.

At kid-scale (< 100 entities on screen), the difference is invisible
— everything runs at 60 FPS regardless. At bullet-hell scale (500+
entities), layers matter.

## Reading collisions with layers

`world/collisions` still returns all colliding pairs. Layer filtering
happens BEFORE that list is populated, not on the reading side. So
your `for-each pair` loop is unchanged; it just has fewer pairs to
walk.

## Pitfalls

**Layer defined but not attached.** You wrote the layer-alist but
forgot `entity/layer! e 'name`. Entity uses default layer, doesn't
match the alist rules. Fix: assign layer at spawn.

**Asymmetric layer definition confuses.** 'a hits b' but 'b doesn't
hit a.' The engine has to trigger the pair when EITHER side allows.
Some runtimes require reciprocity. Test both directions of any
new pair.

**All bullets vanish.** Layer for bullets doesn't include ANYTHING
in `:collides-with` list, so bullets have no collisions at all.
Include their targets.

**Layer typo silently fails.** `'plyaer` vs `'player`. The engine
may not warn. Grep your code for consistency.

## The debug-print layer helper

```scheme
(define (print-active-layers)
  (world/each 'all
              (lambda (e)
                (display (entity/kind e))
                (display \" layer: \")
                (display (entity/state e 'layer))
                (newline))))
```

Call once at setup to verify every entity landed on the layer you
intended.

## Rule of thumb

Design your layer alist first, on paper. List every entity type.
Draw arrows for who can collide with whom. Then convert to the
alist. Layer bugs are HARD to debug after the fact; easy to prevent
by drawing.")
